  "doc_id": "1520",
  "text": "It has been hypothesized that the 3′ and 5′ ends are far apart in the context of a \"linear\" flavivirus genome. This may or may not be true. Whole genome RNA fold data suggest that internal base pairing may bring the two ends relatively close together in the \"linear\" form in the absence of the 3′-5′ UAR-DAR-CYC RNA-RNA interactions. The involvement of viral or cell proteins in facilitating the 3′-5′ RNA-RNA interaction has been suggested. Binding of the promiscuous RNA-binding cell protein La [CITATION_1] , the viral C protein (Ivanyi-Nagy and Darlix 2012) and the viral NS3 protein [CITATION_2] to both the 3′ and 5′ RNA ends of flavivirus genomes has been reported. However, unless the proteins binding to each end of the RNA can interact with each other or one protein can bind simultaneously to both the 3′ and 5′ RNAs this does not seem to be a viable mechanism.",
  "correct_citation": {
